  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a very real phenomenon that I've observed throughout my life, especially when I was a young woman trying to navigate the world of science and engineering. It's the anxiety that arises when individuals from a group perceived to be underrepresented in a field experience stress about confirming negative stereotypes about their group's abilities. For instance, when I took my first physics class in high school, the teacher's subtle comments about how 'girls aren't usually good at math' made me second-guess my own abilities, even though I had always been confident in my academic performance. This kind of internalized pressure can significantly hinder performance and discourage people from pursuing STEM fields. I believe we absolutely must address stereotype threat in STEM because it perpetuates inequity and limits the potential of talented individuals. The way to do this is through proactive, inclusive education that normalizes diverse participation from the start. Schools should implement mentorship programs that pair students with role models who share their backgrounds, and teachers should be trained to recognize and counteract biased language. It's also important to create environments where students feel safe to ask questions without fear of judgment. As someone who grew up in a family where my father worked in construction and my mother had only completed primary school, I know firsthand how crucial it is to provide opportunities for all children, regardless of their family background or early educational experiences. By fostering a culture of respect and inclusion, we can help ensure that everyone has the chance to thrive in STEM, not just those who already fit into the dominant narratives.",
